{{distinguish| Andronicus (disambiguation)}}
'''Andronicianus''' ({{lang-grc|Ἀνδρονικιανός}}) was an orthodox [[Christian philosophy|Christian philosopher]] of [[classical antiquity]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | last=Curnow | first=Trevor | title =Andronicianus | encyclopedia =The Philosophers of the Ancient World: An A-Z Guide | pages =24 | publisher =A&C Black | date =2006 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E82oRzHYLhMC | isbn= 1849667713 | accessdate = 2015-12-05}}</ref> He wrote two books critical of [[Eunomius of Cyzicus]] (of whom Andronicianus is believed to be a contemporary) and his devotion to [[Arianism]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | last =Jackson | first = Samuel Macauley | authorlink = Samuel Macauley Jackson | title =Eunomius | encyclopedia =The New Schaff-Herzog Encyclopedia of Religious Knowledge | volume =4 | pages =206 | publisher =Funk and Wagnalls Company | date =1909 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lgGfW-WFjpIC | accessdate = 2015-12-05}}</ref> One book was titled ''Against the Eunomians''; the title of the other is now lost. Nothing more is known of him.<ref>[[Photios I of Constantinople]], ''Codices'' 45.</ref>

