{{about|the Ancient Egyptian official|the Jewish legal definition of nighttime|Hebrew calendar#Measurement of hours}}
[[File:Tomb of Nakht.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Ancient Egypt]]ian women and men wearing [[Kohl (cosmetics)|kohl]], from the tomb of Nakht in [[Thebes, Egypt|Thebes]] (15th century BC).]]
The [[Ancient Egypt]]ian official '''Nakht''' was an 'astronomer' (''Astronomer of Amun''), scribe, and priest during the reign of [[Thutmose IV]], during the [[Eighteenth dynasty of Egypt|Eighteenth Dynasty]].<ref name="baikie1932">{{cite book|first=James|last=Baikie|title=Egyptian Antiquities in the Nile Valley|publisher=Methuen|year=1932}}</ref> He is buried in the [[Theban Necropolis]], in tomb [[TT52]].<ref>{{cite book|last=[[N. de Garis Davies|DAVIES]]|first=[[N. de Garis Davies|SIR NORMAN DE GARIS]]|title=The Tomb of Nakht at Thebes|publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art|location=New York|year=1917}}</ref>

